  <section class="hero">
   <div class="wrap">
    <h1>
     [HI]: Opioid overdose: recognize it, reverse it
    </h1>
    <p>
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: How to spot an opioid overdose and respond with naloxone (Narcan). Naloxone is very unlikely to harm someone, is designed for layperson use, and may reverse an opioid overdose while help is coming. Free to read, print, and share.
    </p>
   </div>
  </section>
  <main id="main">
   <div class="wrap">
    <p class="lede">
     [HI]: An opioid overdose slows or stops a person's breathing.
     <strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Naloxone
     </strong>
     [HI]: is a medicine that can quickly reverse it. It only works on opioids, it is not addictive, and giving it to someone who is
     <em>
      [HI]: not
     </em>
     [HI]: overdosing is very unlikely to harm them — so when in doubt, use it and call for help.
    </p>
    <div class="actions no-print">
     <a class="btn" href="javascript:window.print()">
      [HI]: Print this page
     </a>
     <a class="btn alt" href="naloxone-onepager.pdf">
      [HI]: Download printable PDF
     </a>
    </div>
    <div class="box emergency">
     <span class="tag">
      Call emergency services first
     </span>
     <h3>
      [HI]: Always call for help
     </h3>
     <p>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: If you think someone is overdosing, call your local emergency number (911 in the US/Canada, 112 in much of Europe, 999 in the UK)
      <strong>
       [HI]: right away
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: , then give naloxone. Naloxone can wear off before the opioids do, so professional help is still needed even if the person wakes up.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [HI]: Know the signs of an overdose
    </h2>
    <div class="box warn">
     <span class="tag warn">
      Warning signs
     </span>
     <ul>
      <li>
       [HI]: Will not wake up or respond to your voice or touch
      </li>
      <li>
       [HI]: Breathing is very slow, shallow, or has stopped
      </li>
      <li>
       [HI]: Gurgling, gasping, or snoring/choking sounds
      </li>
      <li>
       [HI]: Lips, fingertips, or skin turning blue, gray, or pale
      </li>
      <li>
       [HI]: Very small, "pinpoint" pupils
      </li>
      <li>
       [HI]: Limp body; cold or clammy skin
      </li>
     </ul>
     <p>
      [HI]: To check responsiveness, call their name, tap or shake their shoulder if safe, and follow local first-aid or dispatcher instructions. If they do not respond and are not breathing normally, treat it as an overdose emergency.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [HI]: What to do — step by step
    </h2>
    <ol class="steps">
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Call emergency services.
      </strong>
      [HI]: Report that someone is unresponsive and not breathing normally, and give your location.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Give naloxone.
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: For nasal spray (e.g. Narcan): tilt the head back, insert the nozzle into one nostril until your fingers touch the bottom of their nose, and press the plunger firmly all the way in.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Support their breathing.
      </strong>
      [HI]: Follow dispatcher instructions. If trained, give rescue breaths or CPR as appropriate. If not trained, keep their airway clear and stay with them until help arrives.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Wait 2–3 minutes.
      </strong>
      [HI]: If there is no improvement (still not breathing or not awake), give a
      <strong>
       [HI]: second dose
      </strong>
      [HI]: in the other nostril.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Put them in the recovery position.
      </strong>
      [HI]: Once breathing, lay them on their side so they don't choke if they vomit.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Stay with them
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: until emergency help arrives. Naloxone can wear off in 30–90 minutes and the overdose can return.
     </li>
    </ol>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      Good to know
     </span>
     <ul>
      <li>
       <strong>
        🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Naloxone is safe to use in an emergency.
       </strong>
       [HI]: It only reverses opioids and is very unlikely to harm someone who has not taken opioids. Do not delay when overdose is possible.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [HI]: It is widely available.
       </strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: In the U.S., naloxone nasal spray is approved for over-the-counter sale and is free or low-cost through many pharmacies, health departments, and harm-reduction programs. Availability varies by country — ask a local pharmacist or health service.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [HI]: Withdrawal may follow.
       </strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Naloxone can cause sudden, uncomfortable opioid withdrawal (sweating, nausea, agitation). Reassure the person, keep them from using more opioids, and keep monitoring until emergency help arrives.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [HI]: Many overdoses involve fentanyl,
       </strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: a very strong opioid. A second or additional dose of naloxone may be needed if breathing does not improve after 2–3 minutes — follow product directions and dispatcher guidance.
      </li>
     </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      Good Samaritan protections
     </span>
     <p>
      [HI]: Many places have "Good Samaritan" laws that protect people who call for help during an overdose from certain drug-possession charges. Protections vary by location — but
      <strong>
       [HI]: calling for help is always the right thing to do.
      </strong>
      [HI]: A life comes first.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [HI]: Be prepared before an emergency
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Carry naloxone if you or someone you know uses opioids (including prescription painkillers).
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Ask a pharmacist or local health department how to get it and how to use your specific product.
     </li>
     <li>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Tell the people around you where your naloxone is kept.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Encourage people not to use alone; if they do, ask them to tell someone or use a "never use alone" hotline where available.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [HI]: Sources
    </h2>
    <ul class="sources">
     <li>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: U.S. Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA) — overdose prevention and naloxone guidance. samhsa.gov
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/overdose-prevention/reversing-overdose/about-naloxone.html">
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) — about naloxone
      </a>
      [HI]: and overdose prevention.
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://nida.nih.gov/publications/drugfacts/naloxone">
       [HI]: U.S. National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA) —
       <em>
        🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Naloxone DrugFacts
       </em>
      </a>
      .
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://www.fda.gov/drugs">
       [HI]: U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) drug information
      </a>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: and over-the-counter naloxone information.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="sources">
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Steps reflect SAMHSA/CDC overdose-response guidance. Always follow the instructions printed on your specific naloxone product, and your local emergency services' direction.
    </p>
    <p class="disclaimer">
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: This guide is general information, not medical advice, and is not a substitute for professional emergency care or training. In an emergency, always call your local emergency number. Hands-on naloxone and rescue-breathing training is widely available and recommended. Reuse and reprint freely.
    </p>
   </div>
